 for bestpractices and # Privacy Policy

## Overview
Create a dedicated Privacy Policy page for LifeOps that presents legal privacy content clearly and accessibly. The page should be a self-contained content page with a clean, readable layout that aligns with the LifeOps design system. It must be robust, accessible, and resilient to partial data. No external API integrations are required for this page, but the implementation should be ready to render rich text sections, headings, lists, and a concise contact/notice area. The page should also provide a clear path to related policy or consent resources (e.g., a Consent Controls link) and be ready for localization if needed.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A static-to-dynamic privacy policy content page that presents sections such as data collection, data retention, user rights, contact information, and a consent controls link.

Goals:
- Communicate legally required privacy information with clarity.
- Provide a digestible, well-structured reading experience on desktop and mobile.
- Align with LifeOps visual language (dark UI, strong typographic hierarchy, accessible color contrast).
- Include a clearly labeled contact/Requests process section and a link to the Consent Controls page.

Connected features:
- No APIs are required to fetch content for this task, but structure the content so it can accept dynamic content in the future (e.g., CMS-provisioned policy sections). Ensure safe rendering for potentially long-form text.

UI elements and how they need to look:
- Policy Text Sections: Clear section headings, subsections, bullet points, and paragraphs describing data collected, retention, data sharing, security measures, user rights, and cookies if applicable.
- Data Collection Subsection: Enumerate categories of personal data, purposes, lawful grounds.
- Data Retention Subsection: Retention periods, deletion schedules.
- User Rights Subsection: Access, correction, deletion, data portability, objection, withdrawal consent.
- Data Processing & Sharing Subsection: Third parties, subprocessors, international transfers (where relevant).
- Security Measures Subsection: Overview of technical/organizational controls.
- Contact Info: DPO or designated privacy contact, methods for submitting data requests, and expected response timelines.
- Consent Controls Link: A clearly visible path to an integrated Consent Controls page (e.g., "Manage your privacy preferences" or "Consent controls").

Visual guidance:
- Use strong typographic hierarchy with readable line length.
- Maintain high contrast text for accessibility (WCAG AA or superior).
- Use the LifeOps design system color tokens and elevation patterns for a dark UI context.
- Include a content-friendly layout that accommodates long-form text, with comfortable line spacing and generous margins on desktop and optimized wrapping on mobile.

## Components to Build
- PrivacyPolicyPage: Main page container with header, content sections, and footer actions.
- PolicySection: Reusable component for a named content section with optional subheadings, paragraphs, and bullet lists.
- DataSectionList: Render a sequence of PolicySection items (data collection, retention, rights, etc.).
- ContactBlock: Subcomponent for displaying DPO contact details and data request process.
- ConsentControlsLink: Accessible link/button component that navigates to the Consent Controls page and clearly communicates its purpose.
- TypographyBlock: Helper for consistent heading/body/meta text rendering per design system.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Framework: React (with TypeScript) is assumed.
- Routing: Privacy Policy route path should be /privacy-policy or similar; ensure it can be nested under a legal/privacy section if needed.
- Accessibility:
  - Semantic HTML: Use main, header, section, article roles where appropriate.
  - Headings: Proper H1 for page title, H2/H3 for sections, with logical order.
  - Keyboard: All interactive elements focusable and operable via keyboard.
  - ARIA: Landmarks and descriptive labels where necessary; avoid unnecessary ARIA unless it improves accessibility.
- UI Components:
